# Explainable Fraud Detection System

> An end-to-end machine learning pipeline for detecting financial fraud on 
> highly imbalanced transactional data — with SHAP-powered explainability 
> that generates human-readable case reports for audit and compliance review.

---

## The Problem

Fraud in transactional data is rare by nature — typically less than 1% of 
all transactions. This extreme class imbalance means standard ML models 
trained on accuracy will simply predict "not fraud" for everything and still 
score 99%+. That's not a model — it's a liability.

This project addresses that core challenge by:
- Reframing the evaluation around **Precision, Recall, F1, and PR-AUC** 
  rather than accuracy
- Using **threshold-based decisioning** to deliberately tune the tradeoff 
  between catching fraud and minimizing false positives
- Making every model decision **explainable** at both the global and 
  individual transaction level using SHAP

---

## What This System Does

1. **Explores** the dataset — class distribution, feature correlations, 
   missing values, and anomaly patterns
2. **Trains and evaluates** classification models on imbalanced data
3. **Applies SHAP** to explain which features drive each prediction — 
   globally across all transactions, and locally for any individual case
4. **Generates automated case reports** — readable markdown files that 
   explain exactly why a transaction was flagged or cleared, built for 
   audit trails and compliance review

---

## Sample Output — What a Case Report Looks Like

The system produces decision reports like this for every transaction:
```
Case 1146 — Decision: FRAUD  
Predicted fraud probability: 1.0000 (threshold = 0.20)

Key drivers pushing toward FRAUD:
  • V8  (value = -37.35) → contributed +18.04 (↑ fraud risk)
  • V14 (value =  -9.07) → contributed +14.42 (↑ fraud risk)
  • V7  (value = -18.75) → contributed +12.44 (↑ fraud risk)

Key drivers pushing toward NON-FRAUD:
  • V1  (value = -13.19) → contributed -11.31 (↓ fraud risk)
  • V22 (value =  -8.89) → contributed  -7.33 (↓ fraud risk)
```

See [`outputs/fraud_case_report.md`](outputs/fraud_case_report.md) and 
[`outputs/nonfraud_case_report.md`](outputs/nonfraud_case_report.md) 
for full examples.

