---

## Key Design Decisions

**Why PR-AUC instead of ROC-AUC?**  
ROC-AUC is misleading on imbalanced datasets because it factors in true 
negatives, which are abundant in fraud data. PR-AUC focuses only on the 
minority class (actual fraud), making it a far more honest performance 
metric for this problem.

**Why threshold = 0.20?**  
The default 0.50 classification threshold is designed for balanced classes. 
Lowering it to 0.20 deliberately increases recall — catching more real fraud 
cases — at the cost of some additional false positives. This tradeoff is 
intentional and mirrors how real fraud operations are run, where missing 
fraud is far more costly than reviewing a false positive.

**Why SHAP over feature importance?**  
Built-in feature importance tells you which features matter on average 
across all predictions. SHAP tells you exactly how much each feature 
contributed to *this specific transaction's* score — positive or negative. 
That per-transaction accountability is what makes the system auditable.

